definition.value: A sphingomyelin in which the sphingoid component is specified as icosasphingosine.
A sphingomyelin in which the sphingoid component is specified as icosaphytosphingosine.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine where the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are palmitoyl and icosanoyl respectively.
A branched-chain saturated fatty acid that is butanoic acid substituted by a hydroxymethyl group at position 2. It is a metabolite derived from the isoleucine metabolism.
The (S)-enantiomer of 2,6-dimethylheptan-1-ol.
The (R)-enantiomer of 2,6-dimethylheptan-1-ol.
An  alkyl alcohol that is 6-methyloctane carrying a hydroxy group at position 1 (the S-stereoisomer).
A D-talopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.
An undecenoate that is the conjugate base of 10-undecenoic acid.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of undecenoic acid.
An apo carotenoid triterpenoid that is 4,4'-diapolycopene in which two of the terminal methyl groups have been oxidised to carboxy groups.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of dodecenoic acid.
A dodecenoate that is the conjugate base of 5-dodecenoic acid.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 20:2 in which the acyl group is specified as (11Z,14Z)-icosadienoyl and is located at position 1.
Any salt derived from a member of the class of dithiocarbamic acids by the formal replacement of the hydrogen of the dithiocarboxy group by a metal.
A polymyxin having a (6R)-6-methyloctanoyl group at the amino terminus.
An alkyl alcohol that is 2,6-dimethylheptane carrying a hydroxy group at position 1.
An adenosine 5'-phosphate that is the monohexadecyl ester of AMP.
Any saturated fatty acid containing 20-26 carbons.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the fatty acyl group is 24 with 1 double bond.
Any carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of lactic acid with the hydroxy group of an alcohol or phenol.
A lactate ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 2-hydroxypropanoic acid with methanol.
Any opine whose structure is based on a sugar phosphodiester.
Any indole alkaloid based on a beta-carboline (9H-pyrido[3,4-b]indole) skeleton.
A member of the class of pyrazoles in which one of the carbons of the pyrazole ring is substituted by an oxo group.
An ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of an alcohol, phenol, heteroarenol, or enol with an organosulfonic acid.
A sphingomyelin d18:1 in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl).
A sphingomyelin d18:1 in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as icosanoyl.
A sphingomyelin d18:1 in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as lignoceroyl (tetracosanoyl).
A sphingomyelin d18:1 in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as hexacosanoyl.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the fatty acyl group is 26 with 1 double bond.
A member of the class of furans carrying dihydroxymethyl and formyl substituents at positions 2 and 5 respectively.
Any member of the class of chlorobenzenes containing a mono- or poly-substituted benzene ring in which only one substituent is chlorine.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any beta-D-glucosiduronic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A metal iodide salt with a K(+) counterion. It is a scavenger of hydroxyl radicals.
A member of the class of cytidines that is a metabolite of the drug capecitabine.
A polyazaalkane that is the 1,5,9,13,17-pentaaza derivative of heptodecane.
A polyazaalkane that is spermidine in which the amino hydrogen at postion 4 is replaced by a 3-aminopropyl group
A polyazaalkane that is spermine in which the amino hydrogen at postion 4 is replaced by a 3-aminopropyl group
Any alkane having a chain length of at least 13 carbon atoms.
Any member of the class of fluorobenzenes containing a mono- or poly-substituted benzene ring carrying a single fluorine substitutent.
An acyl-AMP that results from the formal condensation of the phosphoryl group of AMP with the carboxyl group of any fatty acid.
A carboxamide obtained by the formal condensation of the carboxy group of any carboxylic acid with ammonia.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is CMP in which the 2-keto group on the cytosine ring is replaced by an epsilon-L-lysyl residue.
A phosphatidylcholine 32:2 in which both phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as palmitoleoyl.
A phosphatidylcholine 36:0 in which both phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl).
A 1-acyl-2-octadecanoyl-sn-glycerol-3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl group is also octadecanoyl.
A 1-acyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycerol-3-phosphate(2-) in which the 1-acyl group is also oleoyl.
